[Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) ([Persian language](/Persian_language): شاه عالم دوم, Persian pronunciation: [&#91;ʃɑːh ʔɑː.ˈlam&#93;](/Help:IPA/Persian); 25 June 1728 – 19 November 1806), originally known by his birth name Ali Gohar, or Ali Gauhar, bore the weight of being the seventeenth [Mughal emperor](/Mughal_emperors) and the son of [Alamgir II](/Alamgir_II) [16]. He ascended to a throne that was less a seat of power and more a relic of a bygone era, presiding over a [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) that was not just crumbling, but actively disintegrating around him. The vast imperial edifice, once the envy of the world, had shrunk to a pathetic shadow of its former glory. So diminished was his actual authority during his tumultuous reign that it gave rise to a rather cutting proverb in the [Persian language](/Persian_language): "Sultanat-e-Shah Alam, Az Dilli ta Palam" – a phrase that translates, with a heavy sigh of irony, to 'The empire of Shah Alam is from Delhi to Palam' [17][18]. For context, [Palam](/Palam,_Delhi) was, and remains, a mere suburb of Delhi, highlighting the tragic confinement of his once boundless dominion.

Shah Alam's reign was a relentless parade of invasions, betrayals, and the steady erosion of what little power remained. He faced the formidable incursions primarily orchestrated by [Ahmed Shah Abdali](/Ahmed_Shah_Abdali), a series of events that famously culminated in the brutal and strategically pivotal [Third Battle of Panipat](/Third_Battle_of_Panipat) in 1761. This monumental clash pitted the formidable [Maratha Confederacy](/Maratha_Confederacy) against the Afghan forces led by Abdali. Interestingly, in 1760, the initial invading forces of Abdali were temporarily repelled by the Marathas, under the leadership of [Sadashivrao Bhau](/Sadashivrao_Bhau). It was this Maratha intervention that saw the deposition of [Shah Jahan III](/Shah_Jahan_III), a mere puppet [Mughal emperor](/Mughal_Emperor) controlled by the opportunistic [Imad-ul-Mulk](/Imad-ul-Mulk). Shah Alam II was then installed as the "rightful" emperor (1760–1772), a title that carried more symbolic weight than actual command [19][20].

Despite being widely acknowledged as the legitimate emperor, a title that felt increasingly like a cosmic joke, Shah Alam II found himself unable to return to his ancestral capital, Delhi, until 1772. His return, when it finally happened, was not a triumphant procession but rather a reluctant homecoming, facilitated and protected by the powerful [Maratha](/Maratha) general, [Mahadaji Shinde](/Mahadaji_Shinde). His reign was also marked by direct confrontation with the burgeoning European powers; he notably engaged the formidable [East India Company](/East_India_Company) at the ill-fated [Battle of Buxar](/Battle_of_Buxar) in 1764. Perhaps the most horrifying indignity, a truly visceral symbol of his empire's collapse, occurred in 1788 when, as a prisoner of the brutal [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir), he was cruelly blinded.

Beyond the ceaseless political maelstrom, Shah Alam II possessed a more contemplative, artistic side. He authored his own [Diwan](/Diwan_(poetry))—a collection of poems—and adopted the evocative pen-name *Aftab*, meaning 'Sun'. His poetic endeavors were carefully guided, compiled, and preserved by Mirza Fakhir Makin [21]. Furthermore, Shah Alam is credited with composing the renowned work *Ajaib-ul-Qasas*, a book considered one of the earliest and most significant examples of prose in the [Urdu](/Urdu) language. It’s a curious legacy: a monarch whose political power waned to nothing, yet whose literary contributions endure.

### Early life

Ali Gohar entered the world on 25 June 1728, born to [Shahzada](/Shahzada_(title)) (Prince) [Aziz-ud-Din](/Alamgir_II), who would later become Emperor [Alamgir II](/Alamgir_II), and his mother, Zinat Mahal. His early years, like those of many Mughal princes of the declining era, were spent in a state of semi-captivity within the confines of the Salatin quarters of the magnificent [Red Fort](/Red_Fort). This gilded cage, while offering a semblance of royal upbringing, severely limited the exposure and practical experience crucial for future rulers. However, unlike numerous other Mughal princes who succumbed to the decadent and enervating lifestyle often associated with such restricted circumstances, Ali Gohar managed to maintain a degree of discipline and intellectual curiosity. There is no historical record suggesting he became a mere pleasure-seeker by the time his father unexpectedly ascended to the throne. Consequently, when [Alamgir II](/Alamgir_II) became emperor, Ali Gohar was naturally entrusted with significant appointments, a testament to his perceived capabilities, even if much of the real authority had already slipped away.

Upon his father's accession, Ali Gohar was formally declared the [Wali al-Ahd](/Wali_al-Ahd) ([Crown Prince](/Crown_Prince)) of the empire. He quickly became his father's primary agent, a role that brought him into direct, and often bitter, conflict with the immensely powerful [Wazir Imad-ul-Mulk](/Imad-ul-Mulk). This vizier, a master of political maneuvering and ruthless ambition, wielded almost all effective power, reducing the emperor to a figurehead. The constant friction between the assertive young prince and the dominant vizier, coupled with a very real fear for his own life, ultimately compelled Ali Gohar to make a desperate escape from Delhi in 1758. It was a perilous flight, a royal fugitive seeking refuge from the very court he was destined to inherit.

### Escape from Delhi

Prince Ali Gauhar, the very individual who would eventually bear the tragic mantle of Emperor [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II), was, as established, the rightful heir apparent to his father, [Alamgir II](/Alamgir_II). However, his father's elevation to the [Mughal Emperor](/Mughal_Emperor)'s throne had been orchestrated not by divine right or popular acclaim, but by the machinations of the powerful [Vizier](/Vizier) [Imad-ul-Mulk](/Imad-ul-Mulk) and the cousin of the Maratha [Peshwa](/Peshwa), [Sadashivrao Bhau](/Sadashivrao_Bhau) [22]. This external influence meant that [Alamgir II](/Alamgir_II)'s reign was inherently unstable, a precarious arrangement that left little room for his son to assert any meaningful authority.

Recognizing the futility of remaining a pawn in Delhi, Prince Ali Gauhar took matters into his own hands. He assembled a rudimentary militia and executed a daring escape from the capital, a move that spoke volumes about the desperate state of affairs for the imperial family. By 1759, he had reappeared in the Eastern [Subah](/Subah) (provinces), harboring an ambitious, if perhaps naive, hope of consolidating his position by attempting to regain control over the breakaway regions of [Bengal](/Bengal_Subah), [Bihar](/Bihar), and [Odisha](/Odisha). This venture was a desperate gamble, a bid to carve out a sphere of influence beyond the direct clutches of the powerful vizier.

Meanwhile, back in Delhi, the political landscape continued its chaotic churn. Very soon after Ali Gauhar's escape, the influential [Najib-ud-Daula](/Najib-ud-Daula) managed to gather a substantial [Mughal Army](/Mughal_Army) outside the capital. With this force, he compelled the usurper [Imad-ul-Mulk](/Imad-ul-Mulk) to flee, effectively deposing the 'recreant' [Shah Jahan III](/Shah_Jahan_III), who had been another puppet of the vizier. [Najib-ud-Daula](/Najib-ud-Daula) and other prominent Muslim nobles then turned their attention to the formidable Maratha threat. They initiated a strategic correspondence with the powerful Afghan ruler [Ahmad Shah Durrani](/Ahmad_Shah_Durrani), hoping to forge an alliance that could decisively defeat the Marathas. Following Durrani's crushing victory over the Marathas at the [Third Battle of Panipat](/Third_Battle_of_Panipat), he formally nominated Ali Gauhar as the legitimate emperor, bestowing upon him the grand, yet largely hollow, title of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) [23].

### Bengal War

The year 1760 saw Prince Ali Gauhar, now nominally [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II), attempting to exert what little influence he could. His militia, having managed to secure control over scattered pockets of territory in [Bengal](/Bengal), [Bihar](/Bihar), and parts of [Odisha](/Odisha), represented a fragile assertion of imperial authority. The prince and his accompanying [Mughal Army](/Mughal_Army), numbering around 30,000, harbored the explicit intention of overthrowing [Mir Jafar](/Mir_Jafar) and his erstwhile ally [Imad-ul-Mulk](/Imad-ul-Mulk). This was a direct response to their earlier attempts to capture or even assassinate the prince during his advance towards [Awadh](/Awadh) and [Patna](/Patna) in 1759. However, this internal Mughal power struggle was soon complicated, and ultimately overshadowed, by the aggressive intervention of the increasingly assertive [East India Company](/East_India_Company).

The imperial forces, under Prince Ali Gauhar, were unequivocally aiming to reclaim the breakaway Eastern [Subah](/Subah). He was supported by a diverse [Militia](/Militia) comprising notable figures such as Muhammad Quli Khan, Kadim Husein, Kamgar Khan, Hidayat Ali, Mir Afzal, and the chronicler Ghulam Husain Tabatabai. Their ranks were further bolstered by the contingents provided by powerful regional allies: [Shuja-ud-Daula](/Shuja-ud-Daula) (the [Nawab of Awadh](/Nawab_of_Awadh)), [Najib-ud-Daula](/Najib-ud-Daula), and Ahmad Khan Bangash. Adding another layer of complexity to this already tangled conflict, the Mughals also benefited from the assistance of [Jean Law](/Jean_Law_de_Lauriston) and a contingent of 200 Frenchmen, who were actively waging a campaign against the British during the global [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War) [24]. This convergence of interests transformed a regional dispute into a broader geopolitical struggle.

Prince Ali Gauhar's forces initially achieved considerable success, advancing as far as [Patna](/Patna). He subsequently laid siege to the city with a combined army exceeding 40,000 men, his objective being the capture or elimination of Ramnarian, a staunch adversary of the Mughal cause. [Mir Jafar](/Mir_Jafar), understandably terrified by the imminent collapse of his ally, dispatched his own son, Miran, to relieve Ramnarian and attempt to retake [Patna](/Patna). Desperate, [Mir Jafar](/Mir_Jafar) also appealed to the formidable [Robert Clive](/Robert_Clive) for aid. However, it was Major [John Caillaud](/John_Caillaud) who ultimately proved decisive, dispersing Prince Ali Gauhar's army in 1761 after a series of four significant engagements, including the [Battle of Patna](/Battle_of_Patna), Battle of Sirpur, Battle of Birpur, and Battle of Siwan.

Following these military setbacks, negotiations ensued, ultimately leading to a fragile peace. [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) was then escorted by the British to meet [Mir Qasim](/Mir_Qasim), who had been nominated as the new [Nawab of Bengal](/Nawab_of_Bengal) after the sudden demise of Miran. [Mir Qasim](/Mir_Qasim) quickly secured the Mughal Emperor's formal investiture as the [Subedar](/Subedar) (governor) of [Bengal](/Bengal_Subah), [Bihar](/Bihar), and [Odisha](/Odisha), agreeing to pay a substantial annual revenue of 2.4 million *dam*. [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II), in turn, retreated to [Allahabad](/Allahabad), where he remained under the protection of [Shuja-ud-Daula](/Shuja-ud-Daula), the [Nawab of Awadh](/Nawab_of_Awadh), from 1761 until 1764. During this period, [Mir Qasim](/Mir_Qasim)'s relationship with the [East India Company](/East_India_Company) rapidly deteriorated. He embarked on a series of reforms designed to challenge British economic dominance, notably revoking the tax exemptions previously enjoyed by the Company. He also ousted Ramnarian and established [firelock](/Firelock) manufacturing facilities at [Patna](/Patna), explicitly aiming to modernize and improve the newly reformed [Mughal Army](/Mughal_Army).

These assertive actions deeply angered the [East India Company](/East_India_Company), which swiftly moved to depose [Mir Qasim](/Mir_Qasim). Through a web of court intrigues and political pressure, the Company succeeded in forcing [Mir Qasim](/Mir_Qasim) to relinquish his control over [Bengal](/Bengal_Subah), [Bihar](/Bihar), and [Odisha](/Odisha). In response, [Mir Qasim](/Mir_Qasim) actively encouraged [Shuja-ud-Daula](/Shuja-ud-Daula), the [Nawab of Awadh](/Nawab_of_Awadh), and [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) to unite and confront the formidable British presence.

*   [Imad-ul-Mulk](/Imad-ul-Mulk) was the regent imposed by the [Maratha Confederacy](/Maratha_Confederacy) in 1757, a figure infamous for assassinating [Alamgir II](/Alamgir_II) and other prominent members of the imperial family within the Maratha-controlled city of [Delhi](/Delhi). [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) managed to escape this bloody purge, finding precarious safety with the [Nawab of Awadh](/Nawab_of_Awadh) [25].
*   [Mir Jafar](/Mir_Jafar), his son Miran, and Ramnarian, displaying a singular lack of foresight, refused to submit to the authority of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II). This defiance ultimately ignited the [Bengal War](/Bengal_War), an escalating conflict that inevitably drew in the ever-present, ever-opportunistic [East India Company](/East_India_Company).

### Emperor from Allahabad

*Mughal* era illustration of [Pir Ghazi](/Pir_Gazi) of [Bengal](/Bengal), during the 18th century. A visual echo of a time when the emperor's reach, however nominal, still inspired art.

Following the initial tumultuous years and his retreat from Delhi, [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) was, for a time, acknowledged as the legitimate emperor by the powerful [Durrani Empire](/Durrani_Empire). This recognition, while politically significant, was largely symbolic, a nod to tradition rather than a concession of actual power. His nominal rule, a grand illusion, was said to extend over a truly vast and disparate collection of territories. These included the [24 Parganas](/24_Parganas) of the [Sundarbans](/Sundarbans) [26], the domains of [Mir Qasim](/Mir_Qasim) and the [Nawabs of Bengal and Murshidabad](/Nawabs_of_Bengal_and_Murshidabad) (including [Bihar](/Bihar)) [26], the [Raja](/Raja) of [Banares](/Varanasi) [27], the [Nizam of Hyderabad](/Nizam_of_Hyderabad), the [Nawab of Ghazipur](/Ghazipur), the [Sahib of Punjab](/List_of_monarchs_of_Punjab), and even the distant realms of [Hyder Ali](/Hyder_Ali)'s [Mysore](/Mysore) [27]. Further south, his imperial shadow supposedly fell upon the [Nawab of Kadapa](/Kadapa) and the [Nawab of Kurnool](/Kurnool), the [Nawab of the Carnatic](/Nawab_of_the_Carnatic) of [Arcot](/Arcot) and [Nellore](/Nellore) [28], the [Raja of Kashmir](/List_of_monarchs_of_Kashmir), the [Nawab of Junagarh](/Nawab_of_Junagarh), and the various [Rohilkhand](/Rohilkhand) territories of both the Lower and Upper Doab, as well as the [Nawab of Bhawalpur](/Bahawalpur). It was a map of aspirations, not realities, a testament to the lingering respect for the Mughal name even as its practical authority had vanished like smoke.

### Battle of Buxar

Main article: [Battle of Buxar](/Battle_of_Buxar)

The [Battle of Buxar](/Battle_of_Buxar), fought on 22 October 1764, stands as a grim monument to the unraveling of Mughal power and the ascendancy of a new colonial force. This pivotal engagement pitted a formidable, if somewhat disparate, combined army against the forces of the [East India Company](/East_India_Company). The allied Indian forces comprised the armies of [Mir Qasim](/Mir_Qasim), the deposed [Nawab of Bengal](/Nawab_of_Bengal); [Shuja-ud-Daula](/Shuja-ud-Daula), the [Nawab of Awadh](/Nawab_of_Awadh) and the influential [Vizier](/Vizier) of the Mughal realm; and, crucially, the [Mughal Emperor](/Mughal_Emperor) [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) himself. Arrayed against them were the disciplined, well-led forces of the [East India Company](/East_India_Company), under the shrewd command of [Hector Munro](/Hector_Munro,_8th_of_Novar) [29]. The battle unfolded near [Buxar](/Buxar), a town strategically situated on the bank of the [Ganges river](/Ganges), then considered within the territory of [Bengal](/Bengal). The outcome was not merely a victory, but a crushing, decisive triumph for the [East India Company](/East_India_Company), effectively sealing the fate of vast swathes of the subcontinent and marking a critical turning point in British colonial expansion in India. It was a stark demonstration that even a combined force of the emperor and powerful regional rulers was no match for the Company's military might.

*   [Shuja-ud-Daula](/Shuja-ud-Daula) served as the preeminent [Nawab](/Nawab) [Vizier](/Vizier) of the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire), playing a critical, if ultimately tragic, role during both the [Third Battle of Panipat](/Third_Battle_of_Panipat) and the devastating [Battle of Buxar](/Battle_of_Buxar).
*   [Nawab of Bengal](/Nawab_of_Bengal), [Mir Qasim](/Mir_Qasim), in a desperate bid to resist the British, defected to the side of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II), forming part of the ill-fated alliance at Buxar.
*   [Mirza Najaf Khan](/Mirza_Najaf_Khan), the commander-in-chief of the [Mughal Army](/Mughal_Army), a figure of considerable military acumen, found himself leading forces against an inevitable tide.

### Treaty of Allahabad

Main article: [Treaty of Allahabad](/Treaty_of_Allahabad)

In the immediate aftermath of the catastrophic [Battle of Buxar](/Battle_of_Buxar), a defeated and vulnerable [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II), a sovereign who had just seen his nominal authority shattered by the British, found himself with little recourse but to seek their "protection." This protection came at an exorbitant price, codified in the infamous [Treaty of Allahabad](/Treaty_of_Allahabad), signed in the year 1765. Under duress, [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) was compelled to grant the *Diwani*—the right to collect revenue—of [Bengal](/Bengal) (a vast province that then encompassed [Bihar](/Bihar) and [Odisha](/Odisha)) to the [East India Company](/East_India_Company). In return for this immense concession, which handed over the financial lifeblood of one of India's richest regions, the Company grudgingly agreed to pay a paltry annual tribute of 2.6 million rupees from the collected revenue. Furthermore, the Company's coveted tax exemption status, a source of much contention with local rulers, was formally reinstated. Not content with this, the Company also secured the districts of Kora and [Allahabad](/Allahabad), thereby expanding its tax-collecting dominion over an additional 20 million people.

With a stroke of a pen, the [East India Company](/East_India_Company) officially transformed itself from a trading entity into the de facto Imperial tax collector in the erstwhile Mughal province of [Bengal](/Bengal) (which, it bears repeating, included [Bihar](/Bihar) and the northern parts of [Odisha](/Odisha)). To manage this new administrative burden, the Company appointed a local deputy, [Nawab](/Nawab) Muhammad Reza Khan, to collect revenue on their behalf, further entrenching their control while maintaining a veneer of local administration. It was a masterstroke of colonial diplomacy, stripping the emperor of his economic power while leaving him with the empty shell of his title.

*   [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) granting [Robert Clive](/Robert_Clive) the "[Diwani](/Dewan) rights of [Bengal](/Bengal), [Behar](/Behar) and [Odisha](/Odisha)" in return for the annexed territories of the [Nawab of Awadh](/Nawab_of_Awadh) following the [Battle of Buxar](/Battle_of_Buxar), on that fateful day of 12 August 1765 at [Benares](/Benares). A moment captured in art, forever immortalizing the transfer of power.
*   A member of the [East India Company](/East_India_Company) enjoying a [Durbar](/Durbar_(court)). The image speaks volumes: the British, once supplicants, now held court, their presence a stark reminder of who truly commanded the stage.

### Absence from Delhi

The forced absence of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) from his imperial capital, Delhi, was a direct and humiliating consequence of the terms dictated by the treaty he had been compelled to sign with the British. This period of expatriation, lasting for over a decade, underscored the emperor's profound loss of direct control and the symbolic degradation of his once-unassailable position. For the subsequent 12 years, the imperial presence in Delhi was maintained not by the emperor himself, but by his son and heir apparent, Prince [Mirza Jawan Bakht](/Mirza_Jawan_Bakht_(born_1749)), who acted as a regent, alongside the influential and loyal [Najib-ul-Daula](/Najib-ul-Daula). Their efforts, however commendable, could not fully mask the emperor's effective exile, nor could they halt the inexorable decline of the Mughal state's central authority. The capital, once the beating heart of a vast empire, now functioned under the shadow of a distant, disempowered monarch.

### Bengal Famine

The [Great Bengal famine of 1770](/Great_Bengal_famine_of_1770) was not merely a catastrophic natural disaster; it was a profound human tragedy that served as a chilling harbinger of the final collapse of the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) and the descent into widespread disorder across the entire [Indian subcontinent](/Indian_subcontinent). This famine, exacerbated by the exploitative revenue policies of the [East India Company](/East_India_Company) and a callous disregard for the welfare of the populace, claimed millions of lives and devastated the economic and social fabric of [Bengal](/Bengal). Its horror resonated far beyond the immediate suffering, symbolizing the moral bankruptcy of the Company's early rule and highlighting the utter powerlessness of the Mughal emperor to protect his subjects. It was a stark, undeniable signal that the old order had not just weakened, but had failed entirely, leaving a void that would soon be filled by a new, more ruthless power.

### Return to Delhi

[Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) languished in the relative safety of the [Allahabad](/Allahabad) fort for six years, a monarch in exile, far from the symbolic heart of his empire. Meanwhile, the [East India Company](/East_India_Company) continued its relentless expansion. In 1774, [Warren Hastings](/Warren_Hastings), a figure of immense influence and ambition, was appointed as the first Governor-General of [Bengal](/Bengal). This era was characterized by the notorious "Dual Rule," a system where the [East India Company](/East_India_Company) held the reins of power, enacting laws primarily designed to maximize revenue collection, while the Mughal-appointed [Nawab](/Nawab) was left to manage the less lucrative, often thankless, local administrative affairs of the province. It was a cynical division of labor, ensuring British profit while offloading the burden of governance.

The Company, growing ever more confident in its dominance, soon discontinued the annual tribute of 2.6 million Rupees to the emperor, a clear repudiation of their earlier agreement and a further degradation of his status. To add insult to injury, they then handed over the districts of [Allahabad](/Allahabad) and [Kora](/Kora_Jahanabad) to the [Nawab of Awadh](/Nawab_of_Awadh). These actions collectively amounted to a blatant rejection of the Company's nominal vassalage to the emperor as his *Diwan* (tax collector). By 1793, the [East India Company](/East_India_Company) felt sufficiently powerful to abolish the *Nizamat* (local rule) entirely, formally annexing [Bengal](/Bengal). A weakened and utterly dependent [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) could only agree to the Company's "consultation," which, unsurprisingly, advised him never to place his trust in the [Marathas](/Maratha).

Yet, fate, or perhaps sheer desperation, often forces strange alliances. In 1771, the [Marathas](/Maratha), under the formidable leadership of [Mahadaji Shinde](/Mahadaji_Shinde), made a powerful resurgence into northern India, even managing to capture [Delhi](/Delhi). This presented [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) with a grim choice: remain a British puppet in [Allahabad](/Allahabad) or return to his capital under the protection of his erstwhile rivals. He chose the latter, leaving [Allahabad](/Allahabad) in May 1771 and, escorted by [Mahadaji Shinde](/Mahadaji_Shinde), finally reaching Delhi in January 1772. This return, while restoring him to his throne, irrevocably linked his destiny to the Marathas. Together with his new protectors, they embarked on campaigns to reclaim crown lands, notably in [Rohilkhand](/Rohilkhand), where they defeated [Zabita Khan](/Zabita_Khan) and captured the strategically important [fort of Pathargarh](/Pathargarh_Fort), along with its considerable treasure.

Thus, the emperor returned to his ancestral throne in Delhi in 1772, not as an independent ruler, but firmly under the protective, yet controlling, wing of the [Maratha](/Maratha) general [Mahadaji Shinde](/Mahadaji_Shinde) [30]. From this point onward, the emperor became a client of the Marathas, whose [Peshwa](/Peshwa) (prime minister) openly demanded tribute. The Mughals, in their diminished state, were known to have paid this tribute, a pragmatic concession to avoid any further, and likely futile, conflict with the powerful [Maratha Confederacy](/Maratha_Confederacy).

Following the dramatic execution of [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir) and the second restoration of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) to his throne, a permanent [Maratha](/Maratha_Empire) garrison was established in [Delhi](/Delhi) in 1788. This force effectively ruled north India for the next two decades, maintaining a fragile order until their own power was ultimately usurped by the ever-encroaching [East India Company](/East_India_Company) during the [Second Anglo-Maratha War](/Second_Anglo-Maratha_War) in 1803 [31]. The wheel of fortune, it seemed, was perpetually turning against the Mughals.

