### Reformation of the Mughal Army

One of the most pressing, and arguably most prudent, actions undertaken by [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) upon his return to Delhi was the concerted effort to strengthen and revitalize the remnants of the [Mughal Army](/Mughal_Army). This critical task was entrusted to the capable hands of [Mirza Najaf Khan](/Mirza_Najaf_Khan), a general whose military acumen offered a brief, flickering hope for the beleaguered empire. Under his command, a new imperial army began to take shape, moving away from outdated tactics and embracing more contemporary military practices. This reformed force notably comprised infantrymen who were proficient in the simultaneous and coordinated use of both modern [Flintlocks](/Flintlock) and traditional [Talwars](/Talwar) (curved swords) in combat formations [32]. Their logistical capabilities were also adapted; they increasingly relied on elephants for transportation, a practical choice in the Indian terrain, and reduced their former heavy dependence on cumbersome artillery and cavalry, which had proven less effective in recent conflicts. [Mirza Najaf Khan](/Mirza_Najaf_Khan) is particularly credited with introducing the more efficient [Firelock](/Firelock) muskets into the Mughal arsenal, a crucial technological upgrade achieved through his earlier collaboration with [Mir Qasim](/Mir_Qasim), the [Nawab of Bengal](/Nawab_of_Bengal) [33]. These reforms, however, were a valiant but ultimately insufficient attempt to stem the tide against a technologically superior and increasingly organized British force.

