### Foreign relations

[Mughal Emperor](/Mughal_Emperor) [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) negotiates with the [East India Company](/East_India_Company), after the arrival of [Suffren](/Pierre_Andr%C3%A9_de_Suffren). A perpetual state of negotiation, always from a position of weakness.

The complex web of foreign relations during [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II)'s reign often saw him caught between competing European powers, each vying for influence and control over the subcontinent. During his ambitious campaign to regain the Eastern [Subahs](/Subah) (provinces) in the context of the global [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War), [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) received significant, if ultimately insufficient, support from [Jean Law de Lauriston](/Jean_Law_de_Lauriston) and a contingent of 200 [Frenchmen](/French_people). The strategic mind behind this particular alliance was Ghulam Husain Tabatabai, a figure who had shrewdly acquired considerable administrative and military experience from both the French and the [Dutch](/Netherlands), making him a valuable, albeit ultimately unsuccessful, advisor.

However, after [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II)'s crushing defeat at the [Battle of Buxar](/Battle_of_Buxar), the [French](/France) once again extended a hand of potential alliance to the beleaguered emperor. This renewed overture came in 1781, spearheaded by [Pierre André de Suffren](/Pierre_Andr%C3%A9_de_Suffren), a brilliant French admiral. Suffren initiated an ambitious plan: to capture key British strongholds like [Bombay](/Bombay) and [Surat](/Surat) from the combined forces of the [Maratha Confederacy](/Maratha_Confederacy) (who were by then often aligned with the British) and the [British](/Kingdom_of_Great_Britain). This grand strategy envisioned the active cooperation of [Mirza Najaf Khan](/Mirza_Najaf_Khan), the capable Mughal commander-in-chief. The broader aim was to draw [Asaf Jah II](/Asaf_Jah_II) (the [Nizam of Hyderabad](/Nizam_of_Hyderabad)) into an alliance with [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) and the French, thereby assisting [Hyder Ali](/Hyder_Ali) (the formidable ruler of [Mysore](/Mysore)) in his ongoing efforts to capture [Madras](/Madras) from the [East India Company](/East_India_Company) [34]. It was a grand, multi-pronged strategy that, had it materialized, might have significantly altered the course of Indian history. Yet, the persistent internal conflicts and debilitating intrigues within the Mughal imperial court proved to be insurmountable obstacles, preventing the emperor from ever making such a bold and decisive move against the British. The empire's decay was not just external; it was deeply rooted within.

*   [Pierre André de Suffren](/Pierre_Andr%C3%A9_de_Suffren), a formidable French admiral and a crucial ally of both [Hyder Ali](/Hyder_Ali) and, by extension, [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II). His strategic vision was often hampered by the realities on the ground.
*   [Hyder Ali](/Hyder_Ali), a powerful and independent ruler, was bestowed the grand titles of Shams ul-Mulk and Amir ud-Daula by [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II). His pro-[French](/France) policies were, in essence, a continuation of the desperate diplomatic strategies the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) had adopted during the relentless pressures of the [Seven Years' War](/Seven_Years%27_War).

### Political turmoil

The reign of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) was a ceaseless struggle against a multitude of internal and external adversaries, each carving away at the remnants of Mughal authority. The political landscape was less a coherent empire and more a patchwork of competing powers, all contributing to the pervasive sense of turmoil.

#### Jats

The [Jats](/Jats), a community rooted in agricultural traditions, had risen in prominence and defiance, initially in retaliation against the perceived religious intolerance pursued by the earlier emperor [Aurangzeb](/Aurangzeb) [35]. Their kingdom of [Bharatpur](/Bharatpur_State) became a formidable regional power, waging numerous wars against the declining Mughal Delhi throughout the 17th and 18th centuries. Their campaigns extended deep into Mughal territories, including the strategically vital city of [Agra](/Agra) [36]. The Mughals, already weakened by their defeat at the hands of the [Marathas](/Maratha) in 1757, found themselves increasingly vulnerable. Mughal possessions and territories in the region were systematically annexed by the Jats, under the dynamic leadership of Suraj Mal.

In a particularly audacious display of their growing power, the Jats laid siege to [Agra](/Agra) in 1761. After a mere 20 days, on 12 June 1761, the beleaguered [Mughal forces](/Mughal_Empire) defending [Agra](/Agra) were forced to surrender to the Jats [35]. The city suffered extensive plundering, with the Jats carrying off immense bounty. Among the most infamous spoils were the two magnificent [silver](/Silver) doors that adorned the entrance of the iconic [Taj Mahal](/Taj_Mahal). These precious artifacts were ruthlessly stripped from the monument and melted down by Suraj Mal in 1764, an act that symbolized not just the loss of wealth but the desecration of imperial heritage [37]. Suraj Mal's son, [Jawahar Singh](/Jawahar_Singh), continued this expansionist policy, further extending Jat power across [Northern India](/Northern_India) and seizing territories in the fertile [Doab](/Doab) region, [Ballabgarh](/Ballabgarh), and [Agra](/Agra) itself [38]. The Jats maintained control over the [Agra](/Agra) fort and other strategic territories close to Delhi from 1761 until 1774 CE [35], a stark reminder of the emperor's diminished reach.

#### Sikhs

The [Sikhs](/Sikhs), a community forged in a crucible of religious persecution, had been in a state of perpetual conflict against Mughal intolerance for generations. This animosity had been particularly inflamed by the beheading of their revered spiritual leader, [Guru Teg Bahadur](/Guru_Teg_Bahadur), at the hands of the Mughals. The simmering resentment boiled over once again in 1764, when the Sikhs launched a powerful offensive, overrunning the [Mughal](/Mughal_(tribe)) [Faujdar](/Faujdar) (military governor) of Sirhind, [Zain Khan Sirhindi](/Zain_Khan_Sirhindi), who fell in battle. From this point onward, the Sikhs became a relentless force, perpetually raiding and extracting tribute from lands as far as [Delhi](/Delhi), practically on an annual basis. Their raids were less about conquest and more about demonstrating Mughal weakness and exacting a heavy price.

In 1771, even before [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) could make his long-awaited return, the [Marathas](/Maratha) had already [captured Delhi](/Capture_of_Delhi_(1771)), reasserting their dominance over the imperial capital. During this turbulent period, [Mirza Najaf Khan](/Mirza_Najaf_Khan), a general of rare competence, had managed to restore a semblance of order to the chaotic Mughal finances and administration. Crucially, he undertook a significant reformation of the [Mughal Army](/Mughal_Army), infusing it with renewed discipline and tactical improvements. These efforts bore fruit in 1777, when [Mirza Najaf Khan](/Mirza_Najaf_Khan) decisively defeated the forces of [Zabita Khan](/Zabita_Khan) and successfully repelled the persistent Sikh raids, providing a temporary respite for the beleaguered empire.

However, the brief period of stability was fragile. In 1778, following a fresh Sikh incursion into Delhi, [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II), displaying a mix of desperation and poor judgment, ordered their defeat. The Mughal [Grand Vizier](/Grand_Vizier), Majad-ud-Daula, marched with a substantial force of 20,000 Mughal troops into hostile territories to confront the Sikh army. This ill-advised expedition led to a disastrous defeat for the [Mughal Army](/Mughal_Army) at the Battle of Muzzaffargarh and subsequently at the Battle of Ghanaur. The mounting casualties and strategic failures forced [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) to reappoint [Mirza Najaf Khan](/Mirza_Najaf_Khan). But just as hope flickered, Najaf Khan tragically died of natural causes, leaving the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) more vulnerable and weaker than ever before.

Earlier, in 1779, [Mirza Najaf Khan](/Mirza_Najaf_Khan) had carefully maneuvered his forces to decisively rout the "treasonous" [Zabita Khan](/Zabita_Khan) and his Sikh allies. In a single engagement, the rebels suffered a devastating loss of over 5,000 men, including their leader, a defeat so profound that they reportedly did not return to threaten the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) during the remainder of commander Mirza Najaf Khan's lifetime. Recognizing the pragmatic reality of the situation, Najaf Khan, in his capacity as prime minister, even granted sovereign rights to the Sikhs as part of a strategic agreement [39].

By 1783, the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) had disintegrated to such an alarming extent that [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) effectively retained direct rule over only the city of Delhi itself. In this dire context, [Farzana Zeb un-Nissa](/Begum_Samru), a remarkable and influential figure, played a crucial role in temporarily saving Delhi from a potential invasion by a formidable force of 30,000 Sikh troops, led by the formidable triumvirate of [Jassa Singh Ahluwalia](/Jassa_Singh_Ahluwalia), [Jassa Singh Ramgarhia](/Jassa_Singh_Ramgarhia), and [Baghel Singh](/Baghel_Singh). However, the reprieve was short-lived. In the same year, [Jassa Singh Ahluwalia](/Jassa_Singh_Ahluwalia) and [Baghel Singh](/Baghel_Singh) laid siege to the city. Upon entering the [Red Fort](/Red_Fort), [Jassa Singh Ahluwalia](/Jassa_Singh_Ahluwalia) symbolically sat on the Mughal throne, at the behest of [Baghel Singh](/Baghel_Singh), and was even accorded the provocative title of *Badshah Singh*. [Begum Samru](/Begum_Samru) once again intervened, appealing to [Baghel Singh](/Baghel_Singh) to show mercy to [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II). [Baghel Singh](/Baghel_Singh) assented, but presented a list of demanding terms: 30,000 of his troops were to remain in Delhi, with the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) bearing the cost of their maintenance; the construction of at least five Gurdwaras; and an annual tax payment of 13.5%. These demands were accepted by [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) and enshrined in a written agreement. Given the Sikhs' understandable reluctance to fully accept the authority of the Mughal court due to the prevailing political instability, [Mahadji Shinde](/Mahadji_Scindia) was eventually granted the regency, with an agreement that the Sikhs would refrain from plundering the crown lands and would instead receive one-third of Delhi's annual revenue [40]. It was a chaotic, humiliating arrangement for the once-mighty Mughal throne.

### Downfall

A silver [Rupee](/Rupee) struck in the name of [Shah Alam](/Shah_Alam_II). A tangible symbol of a power that was more name than reality.

The series of devastating military defeats at [Muzaffargarh](/Muzaffargarh) and subsequently at Ghanaur finally forced [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) to act decisively, albeit belatedly. Orders were issued for the arrest of Majad-ud-Daula, the [Grand Vizier](/Grand_Vizier) whose disastrous leadership had led to these debacles. The emperor then, with a heavy heart, recalled [Mirza Najaf Khan](/Mirza_Najaf_Khan), the one man who seemed capable of salvaging the situation. This led to the former [Grand Vizier](/Grand_Vizier)'s imprisonment on charges of gross miscalculation and, more gravely, collaborating with the very enemies of the emperor. A sum of two million *dam* in stolen revenue was reportedly recovered from him.

It is a lamentable truth that [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II)'s own poor judgment and chronic vacillation played a significant role in his ultimate downfall. [Mirza Najaf Khan](/Mirza_Najaf_Khan), through sheer military genius and administrative skill, had gifted the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) a crucial breathing space, establishing a powerful and well-managed army in its own right. In 1779, this newly reformed [Mughal Army](/Mughal_Army) had decisively routed [Zabita Khan](/Zabita_Khan) and his rebellious allies, who lost over 5,000 men, including their leader, and consequently posed no further threat during Najaf Khan's lifetime [citation needed]. However, upon the general's untimely death, [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II)'s habitual indecisiveness resurfaced. Instead of appointing Mirza Shafi, Najaf Khan's nephew—a man whose valor had been proven on numerous occasions—as the new commander-in-chief, the emperor inexplicably chose a succession of "worthless individuals" whose loyalty and military record were, at best, questionable [citation needed]. These appointees quickly fell into petty squabbles, further destabilizing the fragile imperial structure. To compound this fatal error, the corrupt and treasonous former [Grand Vizier](/Grand_Vizier), Majad-ud-Daula, was inexplicably restored to his former office. He then proceeded to collude with the Sikhs and, with breathtaking incompetence or malice, drastically reduced the size of the [Mughal Army](/Mughal_Army) from over 20,000 to a mere 5,000. This deliberate emasculation of the imperial forces left the [Mughal Emperor](/Mughal_Emperor) [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) utterly at the mercy of his myriad enemies [41][self-published source].

> The respect toward the house of [Timur](/Timur) is so strong that even though the whole subcontinent has been withdrawn from its authority, that no ordinary prince ever intends to take the title of sovereign...and [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) is still seated on the Mughal throne, and everything is still done in his name.
>
> — [Benoît de Boigne](/Beno%C3%AEt_de_Boigne), (1790).

The words of [Benoît de Boigne](/Beno%C3%AEt_de_Boigne) in 1790 perfectly encapsulate the tragic irony of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II)'s reign: a monarch without a kingdom, a name without power, yet still commanding a phantom reverence that prevented his complete removal.

### Shah Alam II blinded by Ghulam Qadir

#### Prisoner of Ghulam Qadir

Main article: [Capture of Delhi (1788)](/Capture_of_Delhi_(1788))

The nadir of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II)'s tragic reign arrived with the horrifying events of 1788. Following the disastrous tenure of Nawab Majad-ud-Daula, the capital fell under the sway of a known and ruthless enemy of the Mughals: [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir), the grandson of the formidable [Najib Khan](/Najib_Khan). With the crucial backing of his Sikh allies, [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir) brutally coerced [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) into appointing him as the [Grand Vizier](/Grand_Vizier) of the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire). This appointment was not a gesture of alliance, but an act of subjugation.

Once in power, [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir) unleashed a reign of terror, systematically ravaging the imperial palaces in a relentless, desperate search for the mythical Mughal treasure, which he believed to be worth an astronomical 250 million rupees. His avarice knew no bounds, and his methods were utterly barbaric. Unable to unearth such a vast sum, and further enraged by the Mughal Emperor's feeble attempts to resist him and his [Sikh](/Sikh) collaborators, [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir) committed an act of unspeakable cruelty: he personally blinded [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) with an Afghani knife on 10 August 1788 [41]. The emperor's screams echoed through the hallowed halls, a chilling testament to the empire's final, agonizing collapse.

[Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir)'s brutality extended far beyond the emperor himself. He subjected the entire imperial family to unspeakable horrors. Three loyal servants and two water-carriers who dared to assist the bleeding emperor were summarily beheaded. According to one harrowing account, [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir) would sadistically pull the beard of the elderly Mughal Emperor, a profound insult in Mughal culture, further emphasizing his contempt for imperial dignity. For ten agonizing weeks, [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir) continued his depraved acts. He stripped the princesses of the royal family naked, forcing them to dance before him in a grotesque display of power and humiliation, an act so profoundly traumatizing that some reportedly chose to jump into the Yamuna river to drown rather than endure the indignity. The honor of the royal family and the last vestiges of prestige of the [Mughal Empire](/Mughal_Empire) reached their absolute lowest ebb.

It was only then, after weeks of unspeakable cruelty, that [Mahadaji Shinde](/Mahadaji_Shinde), the powerful Maratha general, finally intervened. He marched on Delhi, killed [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir), and took possession of the capital on 2 October 1788 [42]. With a grim sense of duty, Shinde restored the blinded [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) to his throne, effectively acting as his protector. In a brutal act of poetic justice, [Mahadaji Shinde](/Mahadaji_Shinde) sent the severed ears and gouged-out eyes of [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir) to the blinded [Shah Alam](/Shah_Alam_II) [43], a grim trophy for a monarch who had lost everything.

#### Client of Mahadji Shinde

In the aftermath of [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir)'s horrifying atrocities, a grateful, if deeply traumatized, [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) bestowed upon [Mahadaji Shinde](/Mahadaji_Shinde) titles of immense significance: *Vakil-ul-Mutlaq* (Regent of the Empire) and *Amir-ul-Amara* (Head of the Umara). These were grand titles, indeed, but they merely formalized the reality of Maratha dominance. The emperor also entered into a formal agreement with the [Peshwa](/Peshwa), granting tribute to [Pune](/Pune), the Maratha capital, in exchange for the continued protection provided by [Mahadaji Shinde](/Mahadaji_Shinde) and the broader [Maratha Confederacy](/Maratha_Confederacy). It was a transaction of dignity for security, a final admission of imperial impotence.

Following the execution of [Ghulam Qadir](/Ghulam_Kadir) and the second, albeit symbolic, restoration of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) to the throne, a [Maratha](/Maratha_Empire) garrison established a permanent presence in [Delhi](/Delhi) in 1788. This force would effectively govern north India for the subsequent two decades, maintaining a precarious stability in the region. Their rule, however, was destined to be temporary, ultimately usurped by the relentless advance of the [East India Company](/East_India_Company) during the decisive [Second Anglo-Maratha War](/Second_Anglo-Maratha_War) in 1803 [31]. The cycle of external powers controlling the Mughal capital continued unabated.

### Second reign

The tomb of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II), in [Mehrauli](/Mehrauli), [Delhi](/Delhi). A quiet resting place, far removed from the brutal theatrics of his life.

The geopolitical chessboard of the late 18th and early 19th centuries saw European rivalries spill over into the Indian subcontinent. The looming French threat in Europe and its potential repercussions in India compelled the British to strategically maneuver to regain custody of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II). The British harbored a very real fear that French military officers, ever opportunistic, might successfully overthrow Maratha power in Delhi and then leverage the symbolic authority of the Mughal emperor to further French ambitions in India. It was a race for legitimacy, even if that legitimacy was a mere shadow.

Despite his physical blindness and profound loss of direct power, [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) remained remarkably well-informed about the political currents shaping his fragmented empire. He engaged in correspondence with [Hyder Ali](/Hyder_Ali) and, subsequently, with his son [Tipu Sultan](/Tipu_Sultan) during their intense conflicts with the [East India Company](/East_India_Company) during the [Anglo-Mysore Wars](/Anglo-Mysore_Wars). These communications reveal an emperor acutely aware of the British's relentless expansionist agenda, even if he lacked the means to counter it effectively.

The inevitable shift in power came after the [Battle of Delhi (1803)](/Battle_of_Delhi_(1803)), a decisive engagement during the [Second Anglo-Maratha War](/Second_Anglo-Maratha_War). On 14 September 1803, British troops marched triumphantly into Delhi, effectively ending two decades of Maratha rule over the Mughals. There, they found [Shah Alam](/Shah_Alam_II), by then a blind, elderly man, seated pathetically under a tattered canopy, a poignant symbol of lost grandeur. He was immediately brought under British "protection." The Mughal Emperor, stripped of all military power and effective governance, was now a mere pensioner, albeit a highly respected one. Yet, his name still commanded immense reverence across the length and breadth of the country, a testament to the enduring legacy of the [House of Timur](/Timur) [citation needed]. The regional [Nawabs](/Nawab) and [Subedars](/Subedar), regardless of their actual independence, still sought the formal sanction of the [Mughal Emperor](/Mughal_Emperor) upon their accession and highly valued the titles he bestowed upon them. They continued to strike coins and read the [khutba](/Khutba) (Friday sermons) in his name, acknowledging his symbolic, if not practical, suzerainty. Even after the British took control, the Marathas, under [Yashwantrao Holkar](/Yashwantrao_Holkar), attempted to dislodge the British from Delhi in 1804 during the [Siege of Delhi (1804)](/Siege_of_Delhi_(1804)), but their efforts ultimately failed.

### Death

[Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II), having endured a life marked by profound loss, political turmoil, and personal tragedy, finally succumbed to natural causes on 19 November 1806. He was 78 years old, an age that must have felt like an eternity given the relentless pressures of his reign. His grave is located within a serene marble enclosure, gracefully adjoined to the [Moti Masjid](/Moti_Masjid_(Mehrauli)), a mosque of quiet dignity. This sacred resting place lies beside the revered [dargah](/Dargah) of the 13th-century Sufi saint [Qutbuddin Bakhtiar Kaki](/Qutbuddin_Bakhtiar_Kaki), situated in [Mehrauli](/Mehrauli), [Delhi](/Delhi). Within the same enclosure, sharing the hallowed ground, are the tombs of two other Mughal emperors: [Bahadur Shah I](/Bahadur_Shah_I) (also known as [Shah Alam I](/Shah_Alam_I)), and [Akbar Shah II](/Akbar_Shah_II) [44]. His passing marked not just the end of a life, but the quiet closing of a chapter, leaving the Mughal name a mere historical echo.

### In popular culture

*   In the 1994 [Hindi](/Hindi) TV series *[The Great Maratha](/The_Great_Maratha)*, [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II)'s character was portrayed by [Rishabh Shukla](/Rishabh_Shukla).

### Gallery

*   Map of India in 1765, before the fall of [Nawabs](/Nawab) and [Princely states](/Princely_state) nominally allied to the emperor (mainly in Green). A fragmented vision of a once-unified empire.
*   Map of India in 1795, 11 years before the death of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II). The green areas shrink, a visual metaphor for his dwindling authority.
*   Blind [Mughal Emperor](/Mughal_Emperor) [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II) sits at throne of [Delhi](/Delhi). A powerful image of dignity amidst profound personal and imperial ruin.
*   Silver Rupee of the [Chhatarpur State](/Chhatarpur_State), struck in the name of Mughal emperor [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II). Even a minor state still acknowledged the ghost of his authority.
*   Silver Rupee of the [Orchha State](/Orchha_State), minted during the reign of king Vikramajit Mahendra, struck in the name of Mughal emperor [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II). More silver, more empty reverence.
*   Silver rupee coins from the [Bengal Presidency](/Bengal_Presidency), struck in the name of [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II), [Calcutta Mint](/India_Government_Mint,_Kolkata). The ultimate irony: his name adorning the coinage of those who had utterly dismantled his power.
*   Silver Rupee from the [Kingdom of Rohilkhand](/Kingdom_of_Rohilkhand), minted in Qasba Panipat, struck in the name of Mughal emperor [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II), with having "saya-e-fazle elah" couplet, Swastika and Parasol marks. A blend of imperial symbolism and regional identifiers.
*   Silver Rupee of the [Bengal Presidency](/Bengal_Presidency), struck in Muhammadabad Benaras, in the name of Mughal emperor [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II). Another testament to the British's clever appropriation of Mughal legitimacy.
*   Silver Rupee of Krishna Raja Wodeyar, [Kingdom of Mysore](/Kingdom_of_Mysore), struck in the name of Mughal emperor [Shah Alam II](/Shah_Alam_II), Zarb Mahisur Mint, AD 1805. Even a powerful southern kingdom, often at odds with the Mughals, still paid lip service to the imperial name.

